subsection.p:
For the coordinate axes,
\boxed{ I_x=\iiint_E (y^2+z^2)\delta\,dV, }
\boxed{ I_y=\iiint_E (x^2+z^2)\delta\,dV, }
and
\boxed{ I_z=\iiint_E (x^2+y^2)\delta\,dV. }

statement.p:
In cylindrical coordinates, 0\le r\le2, \qquad 0\le\theta\le2\pi, \qquad 0\le z\le3. The distance to the z-axis is s=r. So
I_z \amp= \int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^2\int_0^3 r^2\cdot 5\cdot r\,dz\,dr\,d\theta \amp= 5\int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^2\int_0^3 r^3\,dz\,dr\,d\theta \amp= 5(2\pi)(3)\int_0^2 r^3\,dr \amp= 30\pi\left[\frac{r^4}{4}\right]_0^2 \amp= 30\pi\cdot4 \amp= 120\pi.
Thus \boxed{ I_z=120\pi. }

